ities were elevated in fertilized plots$\backslash$nonly within the same season as the initial fertilization pulse. Food$\backslash$nweb structure, as indexed by herbivore:predator ratio, was altered$\backslash$nin plots that received a one-time N subsidy, with the arthropod food$\backslash$nweb in fertilized Spartina taking three years to resemble that of$\backslash$nunperturbed Spartina. The response of particular herbivores and predators$\backslash$nto the nutrient pulse was in part habitat dependent (contiguous Spartina$\backslash$nmeadows vs. isolated islets), suggesting that habitat heterogeneity$\backslash$ncombined with the differential dispersal ability of arthropods can$\backslash$ninfluence the long-term response of a food web to a nutrient pulse.},
